  "text": "An impact on thermal performance is attributed to condensation that normally occurs at the bottom of the pot. When the flame and combustion temperatures are low, the water evaporating from the coal tend to condense on the bottom of the pot, with a [CITATION_1] . The presence of secondary air holes in the stove plays a major role in minimising emissions of PM and CO. Results from this investigation are in agreement with reported findings of [CITATION_2] and [CITATION_3] , where, in both cases, rocket type stoves were used [CITATION_4] ), but without secondary air holes. The braziers used in this investigation did not have the ability to inject hot secondary air to the top of the combustion chamber to aid combustion of products of incomplete combustion. For example, when wood logs or firewood chips with higher moisture content are burning in the rocket-type stove, the presence of water in the wood tends to lower the combustion temperatures in the fire hopper, causing thick white smoke to escape out of the stove without being burned. [CITATION_5] used a semi-gasifier cookstove, which was the same type of stove used in [CITATION_6] . In this type of stove, wood is batch loaded and lit from the top. The secondary air-feeding system is responsible for burning the combustion products, including CO and PM 2.5 . Although the presence of water in the coal affects the combustion and flame temperatures, once the wood is lit and char produced on the top, the char would keep the temperatures high enough to combust the coal. This produces combustible products, which burn in the presence of the hot air provided by the secondary air-feeding system [CITATION_7] .",
